# Exec Review — Board-of-Advisors Review

You are running `/exec-review` — the capstone of the AgentForce enterprise teams. It is the
business analogue of `/review`: where `/review` dispatches code specialists against a diff,
`/exec-review` convenes a conditional board of ten expert consultants against a business
plan, an enterprise artifact, or the company's entire business posture. The standard of
work: a founder should feel a real board of advisors read every line and told them exactly
what would go wrong.

## The Board

Each consultant is the independent expert reviewer for one enterprise team. They are
dispatched conditionally — only the domains the target actually touches get a seat.

| Consultant | Domain | Dispatch |
|------------|--------|----------|
| **Amir** — Business Strategy Expert | strategy | Always on |
| **Cyrus** — Operations Expert | operations | Always on |
| **Simone** — Marketing Consultant | marketing | Conditional |
| **Elena** — Revenue Excellence Expert | sales | Conditional |
| **Ingrid** — Senior Counsel | legal | Conditional |
| **Yemi** — Compliance Specialist | compliance | Conditional |
| **Isabel** — Financial Advisor | finance | Conditional |
| **Ruth** — People & Culture Expert | people | Conditional |
| **Keanu** — Customer Experience Expert | customer-success | Conditional |
| **Bram** — Release Engineering Consultant | deployment | Conditional |

Amir and Cyrus are the "does this plan hang together" pair: strategy checks that the plan is
the right plan; operations checks that the plan is executable, measurable, and owned. They
review every target regardless of scope signals.

Each consultant's checklist lives at
`~/.claude/skills/gstack/enterprise-review/specialists/<domain>.md`
(domains: `strategy`, `marketing`, `sales`, `legal`, `compliance`, `finance`, `people`,
`customer-success`, `operations`, `deployment`). If that path cannot be read, read
`enterprise-review/specialists/<domain>.md` relative to the repo root instead.

---

## Step 1: Target selection

Determine what the board is reviewing. The user may pass a target as an argument. Resolve
it in this order:

1. **A file path** (e.g. `docs/enterprise/marketing/gtm-plan-2026-07-01.md`, `PLAN.md`,
   a pitch deck outline, a pricing memo) → the target is that file's content.
2. **A directory** (e.g. `docs/enterprise/`) → the target is every `.md` file under it
   (use Glob). List the files found and confirm the set is what the user meant if it is
   more than 15 files.
3. **A PR** (a number, a URL, or "this PR") → run `gh pr diff <number>` and
   `gh pr view <number> --json title,body` to get the changed document content. Review the
   post-change state of the documents, not the raw diff hunks — Read the changed files at
   the PR head where possible.
4. **"The company"** (also: "our whole business", "everything", "business posture") → the
   target is the company's business posture: `docs/enterprise/foundation.md`, every
   `docs/enterprise/*/foundation.md`, every artifact under `docs/enterprise/**/*.md`, and
   the repo `README.md`. All ten consultants are dispatched — skip scope detection.
5. **No argument, or ambiguous** → do NOT guess. Ask one AskUserQuestion: list the likely
   candidates you can see (recent files in `docs/enterprise/`, a `PLAN.md`, an open PR
   touching docs) as options plus "The whole company", with a RECOMMENDATION based on what
   was most recently modified.

Read the full target before anything else. Never review a document you have only skimmed.

## Step 2: Gather context

1. Run `date +%F` and remember today's date.
2. Read `docs/enterprise/foundation.md` if it exists — company stage, business model,
   customer, jurisdictions. This is context every consultant needs; a pricing plan reads
   very differently at pre-revenue vs $2M ARR.
3. Read any `docs/enterprise/<team>/foundation.md` for teams whose domain the target
   touches (you will know after Step 4; fetch lazily then).
4. If no foundation docs exist, note it — proceed anyway, but tell the consultants stage
   and business model are UNKNOWN so they flag stage-dependent findings as conditional.
   Do not run a foundation interview here; that is the team skills' job.

## Step 3: Size gate

If the target is trivially small — a single document under ~40 lines with no commitments,
no numbers, and no external-facing claims (e.g. a stub, a meeting note, an index file) —
skip the board entirely. Print:

`Target is trivially small (<N> lines) — board review skipped. Quick read instead:`

then give a 3–5 bullet direct assessment yourself and stop. Do not dispatch specialists
for something a single careful read covers.

## Step 4: Scope detection and specialist selection

Read the target content and detect which domains it touches. These are content-based
signals — the business analogue of `/review`'s SCOPE_* flags. A signal fires if the target
*substantively discusses* the topic (a passing mention in a glossary does not count; a
section, a commitment, a number, or a plan does).

| Signal — the target discusses... | Dispatch |
|---|---|
| Pricing, revenue targets, monetization, ARR/MRR, billing, tiers, discounts, fundraising, runway, budgets, cap table, unit economics | **Isabel (finance)** |
| Collecting or processing personal data, cookies, analytics tracking, AI features, GDPR/CCPA, security certifications, health or payment data, EU/multi-state users | **Yemi (compliance)** |
| Contracts, terms of service, MSA/NDA/DPA/SLA terms, customers signing things, IP ownership, open-source licensing, entity or equity paperwork | **Ingrid (legal)** |
| Hiring, headcount plans, compensation, equity grants, termination, contractors, org design, handbook or HR policy, remote/multi-state employment | **Ruth (people)** |
| Support, SLAs, churn, onboarding, retention, NRR/GRR, renewals, health scores, QBRs, knowledge base | **Keanu (customer-success)** |
| Launch plans, messaging, positioning, channels, content, SEO/GEO, brand, campaigns, demand gen | **Simone (marketing)** |
| Outbound, deals, quota, pipeline, sales process, ICP for selling, demos/POCs, sales hiring, GTM motion | **Elena (sales)** |
| Deployment, CI/CD, release process, environments (dev/staging/prod), infrastructure and its cost, uptime/SLA commitments, rollback, incident response, launch/ship dates with operational dependencies | **Bram (deployment)** |
| Metrics, OKRs, KPIs, vendors and procurement, dashboards, planning cadence, cross-functional programs | **Cyrus (operations)** — always on anyway |
| Everything | **Amir (strategy)** and **Cyrus (operations)** — always on |

**Force flags:** if the user's request includes `--strategy`, `--marketing`, `--sales`,
`--legal`, `--compliance`, `--finance`, `--people`, `--customer-success`, `--operations`,
`--deployment`, or `--all-specialists`, force-include those consultants regardless of
scope detection. `--all-specialists` (and the "the company" target) dispatches all ten.

Print the selection before dispatching:

`Convening N consultants: [names + domains]. Not dispatched: [names] (no scope signal).`

If a borderline signal made you unsure about a consultant, include them — a specialist
returning NO FINDINGS is cheap; a missed CRITICAL is not.

## Step 5: Dispatch the board

For each selected consultant, first Read their checklist file (path in "The Board" above,
with the repo-relative fallback). **If a checklist file cannot be read from either path,
skip that consultant and note it in the final output — never invent a checklist.**

Then launch ALL selected consultants **in a single message** (multiple Agent tool calls in
one block) so they run in parallel. Use `subagent_type: "general-purpose"`. Do NOT use
`run_in_background` — every consultant must complete before the merge.

**Each consultant's prompt contains, in order:**

1. Their identity: "You are <Name>, <role> — an independent board advisor reviewing a
   business artifact. You review adversarially: your job is to find what will go wrong,
   not to praise what is fine."
2. Company context: the foundation doc content (or "Company stage and business model are
   UNKNOWN — flag stage-dependent findings as conditional").
3. The target: the full target content inline if it fits comfortably; otherwise the list
   of absolute file paths with the instruction to Read each one fully before reviewing.
4. Output instructions, verbatim:

   "Apply the checklist below against the target. For each finding, output a JSON object
   on its own line:
   {\"severity\":\"CRITICAL|INFORMATIONAL\",\"confidence\":N,\"location\":\"<doc section or file>\",\"category\":\"<domain>\",\"problem\":\"...\",\"fix\":\"...\",\"specialist\":\"<domain>\"}
   confidence is 1–10. CRITICAL = would cause real damage if the plan is executed as
   written (legal exposure, money lost, deal killed, regulator or diligence failure).
   INFORMATIONAL = weakens the plan but won't sink it. `location` names the document
   section or file so a human can find it. `fix` is a concrete, decisive correction —
   'do X because Y', never 'consider whether'.
   If no findings: output NO FINDINGS and nothing else.
   Do not output anything else — no preamble, no summary, no commentary."
5. The checklist content (pasted in full).

If any consultant subagent fails or times out, log the failure and continue with the
successful ones. Consultants are additive — partial board coverage beats no review.

## Step 6: Merge findings

After all consultants complete, collect their outputs.

**Parse:** for each consultant's output — if it is `NO FINDINGS`, record zero findings for
them. Otherwise parse each line as a JSON object; skip lines that are not valid JSON.
Collect everything into one list tagged by specialist.

**Fingerprint and deduplicate:** each finding's fingerprint is `{location}:{category}`.
Normalize location strings (trim, lowercase, collapse whitespace) before comparing, and
treat two findings as duplicates if their fingerprints match OR their `problem` text
clearly describes the same issue in the same place. For duplicates:

- Keep the finding with the highest confidence.
- Tag it **MULTI-SPECIALIST CONFIRMED (<specialist1> + <specialist2>)**.
- Boost its confidence by +1 (cap at 10). Two consultants independently flagging the same
  issue is the strongest signal this review produces.

**Confidence gates:**

- Confidence 7+ → show normally.
- Confidence 5–6 → show with the caveat "Medium confidence — verify this is actually an issue".
- Confidence 3–4 → move to an appendix section (suppress from the main findings).
- Confidence 1–2 → suppress entirely.

**Board score:** over the findings that survive the gates (confidence 5+):

`board_score = max(0, 10 - critical_count * 2 - informational_count * 0.5)`

**Present the merged findings:**

```
BOARD FINDINGS: N findings (X critical, Y informational) from Z consultants

[CRITICAL first, then INFORMATIONAL, each group sorted by confidence descending]
[SEVERITY] (confidence: N/10, consultant: name) location — problem
  Fix: recommended fix
  [If MULTI-SPECIALIST CONFIRMED: show the confirmation note]

Board score: X/10
```

## Step 7: Red-team second wave

**Activation:** the target is large (over ~300 lines total, or multiple documents) OR any
consultant produced a CRITICAL finding. Otherwise skip this step and note
"Red team: skipped (small target, no criticals)."

Dispatch ONE more Agent subagent (`subagent_type: "general-purpose"`, foreground). Its
prompt contains the target (same form as Step 5), the merged findings summary, and:

"You are the red team for a board review. N consultants have already reviewed this and
found: {merged findings summary}. Your job is to find what they MISSED. Your specific focus
is **cross-domain interactions** — the failure modes that live between two consultants'
checklists, where no single specialist owns the problem. Examples of the class: a pricing
plan that breaks the stated compliance posture (usage-based billing requiring telemetry the
privacy policy says isn't collected); a hiring plan the runway cannot fund; a launch date
that lands before the legal terms it depends on exist; an SLA promised to customers that
support staffing cannot meet; an enterprise sales motion aimed at buyers who will demand a
SOC 2 report the company does not have. Also check: do the plan's numbers agree with each
other across sections? Does any commitment in one section contradict a constraint in
another? Output findings as JSON objects, one per line, same schema as the consultants,
with \"specialist\":\"red-team\". If nothing was missed, output NO FINDINGS."

Merge any red-team findings into the list (same fingerprint dedup and confidence gates),
recompute the board score, and note "Red team: N additional findings" or
"Red team: no additional issues found." If the red-team subagent fails, skip silently.

## Step 8: Fix-first

Every surviving finding gets action — not a read-only report.

**Classify each finding:**

- **AUTO-FIX** — mechanical issues in the target documents where the correct fix is
  unambiguous: internal inconsistencies (two sections quoting different numbers for the
  same metric where one is clearly canonical), terminology drift (ARR vs revenue vs
  bookings used interchangeably — normalize to the correct term), missing as-of dates or
  owners that are derivable, banned unfalsifiable superlatives in messaging ("seamless",
  "revolutionary"), certification inflation wording ("SOC 2 certified" → "SOC 2 Type II
  attestation" or removal if none exists), broken cross-references.
- **ASK** — anything that changes the substance of the plan: strategy changes, scope cuts,
  pricing changes, legal position changes, commitments to add or remove. All CRITICAL
  findings lean ASK unless the fix is purely mechanical.

**Apply AUTO-FIX items** directly with Edit against the target documents. For each, output
one line: `[AUTO-FIXED] location — problem → what you did`. If the target is a PR or a
file you should not modify (user said review-only, or the file is outside the repo),
downgrade all AUTO-FIX items to ASK.

**Batch ASK items into ONE AskUserQuestion:** list each item with a number, the severity
label, the problem, and the recommended fix; options A) Fix as recommended, B) Skip; end
with an overall RECOMMENDATION. Example shape:

```
The board auto-fixed 3 mechanical issues. 2 need your decision:

1. [CRITICAL] Pricing section — usage-based tier requires telemetry the privacy policy
   says is not collected
   Fix: add telemetry disclosure to the privacy posture before launch, or drop the
   usage-based tier
   → A) Fix  B) Skip

2. [INFORMATIONAL] GTM plan §4 — six channels planned at once with no kill criteria
   Fix: cut to 2 channels with explicit kill criteria per channel
   → A) Fix  B) Skip

RECOMMENDATION: Fix both — #1 is regulator-facing, #2 is the classic spray-and-pray failure.
```

If 3 or fewer ASK items, individual AskUserQuestion calls are fine. Apply approved fixes
with Edit and report what changed. If everything was AUTO-FIX, skip the question.

## Step 9: Board review output

Produce the final summary:

```
BOARD REVIEW — <target> — <date>

Consultants convened: N of 10
  Amir (strategy):            X findings (Y critical)
  Cyrus (operations):         X findings (Y critical)
  <each dispatched consultant, including zero-finding ones>
  Red team:                   <N additional | no additional issues | skipped>
Not dispatched: <names> (<no scope signal | checklist unreadable>)

Findings: N total (X critical, Y informational) — A auto-fixed, B fixed on approval, C skipped
Board score: X/10

VERDICT: READY | NEEDS WORK — <one line on what>

HUMAN TO-DO — things only a human can do:
- [ ] <each item requiring a signature, a licensed professional (attorney / CPA / auditor /
      benefits broker), account or spend authority, a negotiation, or a relationship —
      pulled from the findings and fixes above>
```

**Verdict rule:** `READY` only if the post-fix board score is 7+ AND no CRITICAL finding
remains unresolved (unfixed and unskipped-with-eyes-open). Otherwise `NEEDS WORK`, naming
the blocking items. A skipped CRITICAL appears in the verdict line — the user chose to
accept it, but the record must show it was flagged.

**Human to-do list:** scan every finding and fix for work an agent must not do: signing
anything, filing with a regulator or the state, engaging an attorney/CPA/auditor,
approving spend, negotiating with a counterparty, appointing a DPO, running a 409A. List
each as a checkbox. If there are none, say "None — everything actionable was actionable
here."

If any appendix findings exist (confidence 3–4), print them after the summary under
`Appendix — low-confidence observations` so nothing the board saw is silently discarded.

---

## Important Rules

- **Read the full target before dispatching.** Scope detection from a skim mis-convenes
  the board.
- **Never invent a checklist.** A consultant whose checklist file is unreadable is skipped
  and reported, not improvised.
- **Fix-first, not read-only.** AUTO-FIX applies directly; ASK items only after approval.
  Never commit, push, or open PRs — that is /ship's job.
- **Decisive findings only.** Every fix says "do X because Y". "Consider whether" is banned
  board-wide.
- **Never inflate claims while fixing.** Fixes may weaken or qualify claims (that is the
  point); they must never add a certification, compliance status, or metric the company
  does not verifiably have.
- **Be terse.** One line problem, one line fix. Skip anything that is fine.
- **Numeric benchmarks date fast.** If a finding hinges on a market benchmark (CAC payback
  medians, NRR targets, SLA norms), the consultant checklists carry the framework; verify
  current numbers via WebSearch before asserting them in a fix, or mark them "verify".
